The prayer is invalidated by the following in the Ḥanafī school
Losing wuḍū’
If wuḍū’ breaks during the prayer, the prayer breaks immediately, because purity is a condition for the validity of ṣalāh.
Deliberately invalidating one’s wuḍū’
Such as intentionally passing wind or urinating during the prayer. This invalidates the prayer.
The end of a maʿdhūr person’s excuse
If an excused person’s excuse ends during the prayer, the prayer is invalidated, because the prayer was begun on the basis of that excuse.
Finding water after beginning with tayammum
If one started the prayer with tayammum and then becomes aware of available water, the prayer is invalidated.
Expiry of the time for wiping over khuffs
If the permitted period of masḥ over leather socks ends during the prayer, the purification is no longer valid and the prayer breaks.
If masḥ was made over a plaster and one realises the wound has healed
The excuse for wiping instead of washing has ended, so the prayer is invalidated.
If a plaster or bandage falls from a healed wound during prayer, over an area that was farḍ to wash
The prayer is invalidated because the state of valid purification is lost.
Sleep in which ejaculation occurs
This invalidates the prayer because purification is lost.
Insanity
If insanity occurs during the prayer, the prayer is invalidated because legal responsibility and awareness are lost.
Unconsciousness
If one becomes unconscious during the prayer, the prayer is invalidated.
Speaking with human speech
Any normal human speech invalidates the prayer, whether deliberate or accidental, and whether little or much.
Human speech in a real sense (ḥaqīqī)
This means actual ordinary speech, such as talking, answering someone, or making normal statements.
Human speech in a legal sense (ḥukmī)
This is when one says something in the form of duʿā’, but the content is something that could be requested from a human being, such as: “O Allah, give me one hundred dinars.” This invalidates the prayer.
But if one says: “O Allah, forgive me my sins,” this does not invalidate the prayer, because this is not something sought from people.
Returning salām verbally
If one replies to salām with words during prayer, the prayer is invalidated, because this is human speech.
Replying to people in prayer
Such as answering a question, responding to someone, or speaking to another person during ṣalāh.
Speech-like utterances
Sounds such as “āh”, “oh”, “uff”, and similar expressions may invalidate the prayer when they resemble speech.
Crying out in pain or distress
If one cries out because of worldly pain, hardship, or distress, and it resembles speech, the prayer is invalidated.
As for weeping out of fear of Allah or khushūʿ, that does not take this ruling.
Clearing the throat without an excuse
If done unnecessarily, and in a way resembling speech, it invalidates the prayer.
If done due to a genuine irritation or need, it is excused.
Blowing in a way that produces an audible sound
This invalidates the prayer when it takes the ruling of speech.
Coughing or throat-clearing without need
If unnecessary and resembling speech, it invalidates the prayer.
Accepting a correction from someone not in the same prayer
If a person outside the prayer, or in a different prayer, corrects one’s recitation and one takes that correction, the prayer is invalidated.
Audible laughter
If one laughs in a way audible to oneself, the prayer is invalidated.
Loud laughter
If the laughter is audible to those around, it invalidates both the prayer and the wuḍū’, with the known Ḥanafī conditions: that it be from an awake adult in a prayer containing rukūʿ and sujūd. This applies whether deliberate or accidental.
Smiling
This does not invalidate the prayer or wuḍū’, though it is not from proper composure in prayer.
Eating or drinking
This invalidates the prayer because it is contrary to the nature and form of ṣalāh.
Excessive movement
Excessive movement invalidates the prayer when it is not for rectification or necessity. The main definition is that the movement is such that an onlooker would think the person is not praying.
Three consecutive unnecessary movements in one rukn
This is a practical way later scholars describe excessive movement.
Movement not done for rectification
If movement is done for a genuine need connected to the prayer, it does not invalidate, such as going to make wuḍū’ when needed, or killing a harmful creature like a snake.
But excessive movement without such need invalidates the prayer.
Doing an act that destroys the form of ṣalāh
Any action foreign to the prayer which removes the outward appearance of prayer invalidates it.
Turning the chest away from the qiblah
This invalidates the prayer because facing the qiblah is a condition of ṣalāh.
Turning the face away only
This does not invalidate the prayer, but it is makrūh.
Exposure of the ʿawrah
If the amount of the ʿawrah which must be covered becomes exposed for the duration that invalidates, the prayer is broken.
Leaving out any farḍ of the prayer
If any farḍ element of the prayer is left out, the prayer is invalidated, unless there is a valid excuse.
Missing any rukn of ṣalāh
Such as qiyām, qirāʾah, rukūʿ, or sujūd. If a pillar is omitted, the prayer is invalid unless properly restored.
Leaving out a farḍ without excuse, even if without choice
This includes cases where the farḍ is lost during the prayer and cannot be corrected.
An example mentioned is impurity falling onto one’s garment during prayer and being unable to remove it immediately.
A sick person leaving standing due to inability
This does not invalidate, because there is a valid excuse.
An illiterate person not reciting Qur’an due to inability
This does not invalidate, because there is a valid excuse.
If one who was unable to make rukūʿ or sujūd later becomes able during the prayer
If one began the prayer sitting because unable to perform rukūʿ and sujūd, then later becomes able to perform them, the prayer is invalidated and must be restarted, because the prayer began on a weaker basis.
If one did not know al-Fātiḥah and then becomes aware of it during the prayer
For example, a new Muslim who had started with tasbīḥ instead of recitation, then realises he now knows al-Fātiḥah. The prayer is invalidated because the original basis has now changed.
Leaving out a wājib deliberately
This invalidates the prayer.
Leaving out a wājib forgetfully and then not rectifying it with sajdat al-sahw before ending the prayer
If a wājib omission is not corrected properly, the prayer is invalid.
Not doing sajdat al-sahw when it is due
More precisely: if a wājib was omitted forgetfully, and sajdat al-sahw was required but not done before the prayer was ended properly, the prayer is invalid.
Making up a missed sajdah in the final sitting and then ending immediately
If one remembers a missed sajdah in the final sitting, performs it, and then makes salām immediately, the prayer is not valid, because the final sitting must be the final wajib action.
Rather, one must re-establish the final sitting, then complete what is due.
Making a takbīr for another ṣalāh
If a person utters a takbīr intending another prayer while still in the current one, the original prayer is invalidated.
Elongating the hamzah in the opening takbīr in a way that changes the meaning
Such that “Allāhu Akbar” becomes a question, like “Is Allah the greatest?” This corrupts the takbīr and invalidates the prayer.
A grave recitation error
A serious recitational mistake of the type discussed by the jurists can invalidate the prayer.
Reciting from a muṣḥaf while looking into it
In the Ḥanafī school, this invalidates the prayer.
Intending to end the prayer
If one firmly resolves in the heart to leave the prayer, the prayer is invalidated.
Going into an action before the imām and coming out of it before the imām
If a follower goes ahead of the imām in a prayer action and also exits that action before the imām, this invalidates the prayer according to the point you posted.
Going ahead of the imām by one complete rukn
This is also listed as an invalidator in the way you were gathering the rulings.
If one performs an action before the imām, but allows the imām to catch up and leaves it after him
Then the prayer remains valid, though this is blameworthy and against proper following.
A woman praying next to, or in front of, a man in the same congregational prayer
If a woman and a man are both praying behind the same imām, offering the same prayer, then under the known Ḥanafī conditions the man’s prayer is invalidated. The woman’s prayer remains valid. if stood next to each other without any seperator
If one realises during prayer that an earlier farḍ prayer is still owing, while one is ṣāḥib al-tartīb
A ṣāḥib al-tartīb is one who has fewer than six missed prayers. If such a person realises that a previous farḍ prayer is still due, the current prayer is invalidated, because the prayers had to be performed in order.
Cases where tartīb is excused
This invalidation does not apply in cases of forgetfulness, when 6 prayer times pass r when one has six or more missed prayers.
